  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What guidelines are in place regarding passport photos in Canada?",
  "response": "In Canada, passport photos must adhere to specific guidelines to ensure they meet the requirements set by the government. The key regulations include:\n\n1. **Photo Dimensions**: Photos must be 50 mm wide by 70 mm high.\n\n2. **Face Dimensions**: The face must be between 31 mm and 36 mm from chin to crown of the head.\n\n3. **Colour**: Photos must be in colour.\n\n4. **Background**: The background should be plain white or light-coloured with no shadows.\n\n5. **Quality**: The photo must be clear, sharp, with no blurring, and taken with a neutral expression, meaning no smiling, frowning, or gesturing. Eyes must be open and clearly visible.\n\n6. **Lighting**: The lighting must be uniform with no reflections, shadows, or glare, and the photograph must be taken against a properly illuminated background.\n\n7. **Head Position**: The head must be centred and squared to the camera. The photo must show a full front view of the face and top of the shoulders. \n\n8. **Headgear**: Normally, no headgear is allowed unless worn for religious or medical reasons. If worn, there should be no shadows or obscured features.\n\n9. **Clothing**: Avoid wearing white clothing that may blend into the background.\n\n10. **Glasses**: If you wear glasses, make sure there are no reflections and the eyes are clearly visible. If possible, avoid heavy frames and tinted lenses.\n\n11. **Photo Age**: The photo must be taken within the last six months.\n\n12. **Stamp**: On the back of one photo, the name and address of the photographer or photo studio, the date the photo was taken, and not stamped directly on the image must be present.\n\nThese guidelines ensure the passport photo is acceptable for passport processing and international travel security standards. It is often recommended to get your passport photo taken by a professional photographer familiar with these requirements to avoid rejection.",
